<DOC><DOCNO> AP900105-0233 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-01-05-90 1014EST</FILEID><FIRST>u f BC-Britain-Stocks 1stLd-Writethru   01-05 0214</FIRST><SECOND>BC-Britain-Stocks, 1st Ld-Writethru,f0032,0223</SECOND><HEAD>London Shares Lower at Midday</HEAD><NOTE>EDS: SUBS penultimate graf to insert full name, title ofGorbachev; picks up last graf, ``The market ...</NOTE><DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   London share prices were steady at lower levels atmidday Friday, after recovering from early falls induced by Tokyo'searlier stumble.   At about noon London time, the Financial Times-Stock Exchange100-share index was down 10 points, or 0.4 percent, at 2,441.6.   Traders said the index slumped by around 15 points in pre-markettrading, but lack of follow-through selling inspired the market toperk up.   At its best, the index touched a morning peak of 2,448.7 points,before once again moving lower.   ``The market is very nervous and isn't quite sure whichdirection to go in,'' one dealer said.   Volume amounted to 277 million shares by midday, compared with407.5 million shares at the same time Thursday.   Dealers said that many investors were reluctant to get intolarge deals ahead of the release of U.S. unemployment figures forDecember early Friday.   Tokyo's Nikkei index of 225 selected issues closed down 438.12points at 38,274.76 earlier Friday on news that Soviet PresidentMikhail S. Gorbachev has canceled all his January foreignengagements to concentrate on domestic troubles.   ``The market hates political uncertainty,'' one dealer said.</TEXT></DOC>